To help you visualize the "Optical Gate" circuit, here is a schematic representation of how these components connect to form an infrared tripwire.Schematic BreakdownThe Sensor Stage (IR Receiver):Pin 1 (VCC): Connects to the Positive (+) terminal of your 9V battery.Pin 2 (GND): Connects to the Negative (-) terminal of your 9V battery.Pin 3 (OUT): This is your signal line. When it detects the IR beam, it sends a positive voltage to the Transistor's Base.The Switching Stage (NPN Transistor):Base (B): Connects to the IR Receiver's OUT pin. This is the "gate" that controls the flow.Collector (C): Connects to the Negative (-) terminal of the buzzer.Emitter (E): Connects directly to the Negative (-) terminal of the battery.The Load Stage (Buzzer):Buzzer (+): Connects directly to the Positive (+) terminal of the battery.Buzzer (-): Connects to the Collector of the transistor.Key Logic FlowBeam Connected: The IR Receiver sends voltage to the Transistor Base $\rightarrow$ The Transistor turns ON $\rightarrow$ The Transistor creates a path from the Buzzer (-) to Ground $\rightarrow$ Wait, in this configuration, the buzzer is silenced because we have effectively bypassed it or created a path that holds it at a low potential.Beam Broken: The IR Receiver stops sending voltage $\rightarrow$ The Transistor turns OFF $\rightarrow$ The path to ground is severed $\rightarrow$ Electricity is forced to flow through the Buzzer $\rightarrow$ Alarm Sounds.Pro-Tips for Success:Voltage Levels: Since you are using a 9V battery, ensure your IR Receiver is rated for 5V-9V. If your receiver is from a 3.3V system (like the TV stick), you will need a voltage divider or a 5V regulator, or you will fry the sensor instantly.Capacitor Smoothing: As noted previously, add a capacitor across the buzzer pins to smooth out the rapid "data pulses" from the remote so you get a solid tone instead of a stuttering buzz.
